Bid Alert No.:  320212359
Agency Bid No.:  140P6320Q0030
Title:  Notice of Intent Sole Source Fireworks Consulting
Received Date:  03/24/2020
Close Date:  Not Stated
Delivery Point:  24290 DOANE MOUNTAIN ROAD KEYSTONE SD 57751
Download documents online
Bid Documents
Request Future Documents
Specifications:
The National Park Service, NPS NEKOTA MABO, intends to issue a Sole Source award to Weeth and Associates LLC, La Crosse, WI to complete a code review of the permit application, fireworks display operators' proposed fireworks storage and show operation plan for Mount Rushmore National Memorial's July 3, 2020 fireworks display. Weeth & Associates LLC. was the awardee on a prior competitive requirement to evaluate potential discharge sites. In performance of that contract, Weeth & Associates provided relevant information to the State and Park, which is being utilized to apply for the 2020 fireworks display permit. This new requirement is for the contractor who provided all relevant information to provide additional support to the State and Park for finalizing the permit request, procure fireworks, and conduct the display in a safe manner. The Park Service intends to procure the permit and fireworks operations consultation from one source under the authority of FAR 13.106-1(b). This will be a commercial acquisition using simplified acquisition procedures and will be classified under North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) 541611 with a Small Business Size Standard of $16.5 million. This is a Sole Source Notice and not a request for quotations. No solicitation document is available with this notice. Any firm that believes it has the capabilities to provide maintenance and support of this consultation service may contact the Contract Specialist, Julie Gavin at julie_gavin@nps.gov, 605-574-3193 for more information regarding the requirement or specifications. A determination not to compete this proposed order based on responses to this notice will be made at the discretion of the Government. Information received from firms as a result of this notice will be considered for support of the Government¿s determination to support of a non-competitive strategy.

The purpose of the funding is to expandevidence-based, culturally appropriate policy, systems, and environmental strategies that addressthe four National Tobacco Control Program goals: 1) Prevent initiation of tobacco use(including emerging products and e-cigarettes) among youth and young adults; 2) Promotequitting among adults and youth; 3) Eliminate exposure to secondhand smoke; and 4) Identifyand eliminate tobacco-related disparities among population groups at greatest risk. Among thepriority populations at greatest risk for tobacco use is the Native Hawaiian population who areover-represented in nearly all data categories relating to smoking and exposure to secondhandsmoke.The State is seeking interest from a local lead agency (provider) to implement tobacco controlstrategies and activities in Native Hawaiian communities using a population-based approach thatcontributes to changes in social norms and behaviors related to tobacco use and dependence andsecondhand smoke exposure.The request is issued for the purpose of including provider(s) in the federal grant application andif awarded, may result in a contract of up to five (5) years with the provider(s). Emphasis by theapplicant should be placed on implementing community-based policy, system, andenvironmental strategies and activities using a community-led approach to address NativeHawaiians that are disparately affected by tobacco use and dependence and secondhand smokeexposure in a selected community.The interested provider(s) must have a demonstrated track record of successfully working withthe Native Hawaiian population affected by tobacco-related disparities and demonstrate impact/improvement in at least one of the following social determinates of health:a. Access to health servicesb. Access to social support servicesc. Safe housingd. Access to healthy food optionse. Access to transportationf. Job opportunitiesg. Active living opportunitiesh. Public safety

Agency Bid No.:  IFB 20-186 NM
Title:  DTD Freight Advisory Council (FAC) Work Plan Execution
Received Date:  03/24/2020
Close Date:  04/09/2020  02:00 PM
Purchase Type:  One Time Purchase
Estimated Amount:  75000
Delivery Date:  Not Stated
Special Notices:  Questions due date: 03/27/2020 - All or None Award
Specifications:
Purpose and IntroductionThe Division of Transportation Development of the Colorado Department of Transportation (CDOT) seeks contractor services to support and assist in implemention and execution of a 2020/2021 Freight Advisory Council Work Plan.BackgroundCDOT has facilitated the creation of a Freight Advisory Council (FAC) in compliance with the 2015 Fixing America's Surface Transportation System (FAST) Act and at the request of the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA). CDOT provides support to the FAC and dedicates time to the implementation of the FAC Work Plan.The mission of the FAC is:The Freight Advisory Council will serve as a forum for the private sector to advocate for commercial transportation needs, influence transportation policy, and collaborate with partners to develop a transportation system which supports the economic vitality of Colorado by providing for the safe, efficient, coordinated and reliable movement of freight. The FAC aims to: Advise CDOT on freight-related issues, priorities, projects, and funding needs.Educate the public, decision-makers and other stakeholders on the importance of freight, its connection to the economy, and its reliance on the transportation system.Serve as a forum to discuss opportunities and strategies to influence freight-related transportation decisions.Seek opportunities for leveraging partnerships to improve freight movement.Collaborate with other agencies and organizations on data and information sharing to promote informed decision making.Identify short and long term initiatives that will benefit mobility for the freight industry and promote a healthy transportation system.Advise CDOT and other public organizations during transportation planning efforts. The FAC, has a current membership of 38 comprised of freight industry carriers, shippers, elected officials and other key freight stakeholders. The FAC convened in early 2016.The FAC is self-directed by freight industry representatives and provided planning and administrative support from CDOT, via the FAC Secretary and CDOT Office of Freight staff and has strong support of CDOT Executive Management.A change in CDOT's Freight Program leadership in early 2019 resulted in a Lessons Learned exercise with the FAC to see what worked well and what didn't work well, reassess the FAC activities and determine an approach to moving forward. One of the key results and a resounding consensus among FAC members was that the FAC initiatives and activities needed structure. This resulted in the development of a FAC Work Plan that was developed by CDOT in coordination and collaboration with the FAC. The Work Plan was approved by the FAC in August 2019. CDOT recently completed an FHWA approved Colorado Freight Plan in March 2019 that outlined goals for freight at CDOT, and recommended actions and partnerships to promote freight in Colorado. The FAC Work Plan aligns with the goals and strategies outlined in the FHWA approved Colorado Freight Plan.Colorado Freight Plan goals include:

Specifications include, but are not limited to: Spatial Reference Framework:All data will be delivered in the Oregon Lambert coordinate system, international feet. Z unitswill be identical to XY units. The horizontal datum for each survey will be NAD83(2011)GEOID12A, and the vertical datum will be NAVD88, using latest geoid model available fromthe National Geodetic Survey, unless otherwise specified. Data will be delivered in seamlessproject mosaic or tiled scheme approved by Agencys Contract Administrator.Deliverables will include a Report of Survey, Aircraft trajectories, LAS format all-return point files,Ground (Bare-earth) DEM, Highest-hit DEM, intensity image, and formal metadata as follows:The Report of Survey will be a digital text report that describes survey methods; results;Contractors accuracy assessments, including internal reproducibility and absolute accuracy;file formats; file naming schemes; tiling schemes. Requirements for what the Report of Surveymust document, including positions and techniques used is described below.Aircraft trajectories (SBET files) will be in vector file geodatabase format, with aircraftposition (easting, northing, elevation) and attitude (heading, pitch, roll) and GPS timerecorded at regular intervals of 1 second or less. May include additional attributes.All-return point cloud will be LAS 1.2 format files listing all valid returns; all fieldspopulated. For each return: GPS week and GPS second OR Posix time, easting, northing,elevation, intensity, return number, return classification. May include additional attributes. Noduplicate entries. Time will be reported to the nearest microsecond or better. Easting,northing, and elevation will be reported to nearest 0.01 meter (nearest 0.01 feet).Classification of returns will be as complete as is feasible and without avoidable returnmisclassification. 1/100th USGS 7.5-minute quadrangle (0.75 minute by 0.75 minute) tiles.Bare-earth surface model: Raster of ground surface, interpolated via triangulated irregularnetwork from identified ground points. Grids will conform to the following specifications:Esri file geodatabase floating point grid, 3 ft (1m) cell size, snapped to (0,0); andTiled into appropriate logical blocks within the project area. The tiling scheme must beapproved by Agencys Contract Administrator prior to delivery.

Three (3) of these facilities (two City-owned garages, one privately-owned garage conjointly operated withthe City) have existing non-functional VIMOC APGSs that are to be replaced as part of this project. Further details on these VIMOC system replacements are provided in the Specification. Seven (7) City-owned surface lots which currently have no occupancy counting are to have APGSs newly installed. The balance of 10 privately-owned or County of San Mateo-owned garages currently have or will in the future have APGS installed inthem, but the provision, installation and operation of these 10 APGSs is not within the scope of this project. However, a plan for the integration of occupancy information from all these current and future APGSs into the Citys master APGS and wayfinding system is within the scope of this project. The Citys intention is to add occupancy data to the system from the additional privately and County owned/operated garages on a staggered basis over the course of time, as each facility implements an APGS or PARCS system that can provide occupancy data. Bidders are to identify in their pricing proposal either a flat integration cost per additional facility or an hourly rate for additional programing to perform the integration

Agency Bid No.:  0000001002
Title:  Staffing and Efficiency Research Study
Received Date:  03/12/2020
Close Date:  05/07/2020  04:00 PM
Purchase Type:  Term:
Delivery Point:  Minneapolis, Minnesota
Delivery Date:  Not Stated
Special Notices:  Questions Due By 03/23/2020 04:00 PM, Bidder Preregistration
Download documents online
Bid Documents
Attachment 1
Attachment 2
Amendment 1 (03/24/2020)
Specifications:
Specifications include, but are not limited to: 1. Conduct a review of the staffing and operational efficiency of the Patrol Bureau of the MinneapolisPolice Department.a) Conduct a workload-based analysis of current staffing needs in relation to demand forservice. Relevant demand for service factors include but are not limited to crime rates, 911calls, and industry best practice call response times; city population and visitorship precinct,ward, and overall resident population demographics; trends in population density, trends inthe issuing of building permits (residential and non-residential) and liquor licenses; and/orother relevant metrics.b) Recommend staffing levels in relation to demand for service. Forecast future staffing in lightof estimated changes to the demand for service factors described above.c) Review the proportion of time spent by Patrol officers on non-call response activity (i.e.,proactive policing activities, community engagement and procedural justice activities,administrative time, etc.). Recommend the optimal proportion of proactive time for patrolofficers based on peer cities practices, industry standards, and/or research-informed bestpractices.d) Review the efficiency of the current practice of assigning certain investigative functions toPatrol Bureau. Recommend the most efficient and effective organizational model forcompleting these investigative functions based on peer cities practices, industry standards,and/or research-informed best practices.e) Review patrol shifts & scheduling in relation to current demand for service and taskenvironment. If applicable, recommend alternate models that would increase the efficiencyor effectiveness of Patrol activities.f) Review existing administrative and operational business processes to identify pain pointsthat could be streamlined or other potential efficiencies.g) Review the use of overtime to meet staffing needs. If applicable, recommend changes toovertime policies, management, or controls to best use overtime to maximize both costefficiency and scheduling flexibility. 2. Conduct a review of the staffing and operational efficiency of the investigative functions of theMinneapolis Police Department, including the Investigations Bureau, the Forensics Division, andinvestigations personnel housed in precincts and organized under the Patrol Bureau.a) Conduct a workload-based analysis of current staffing needs in relation to demand forservice, attending to factors including caseload, disposition of cases, closure rates, time toclosure, solvability, any of the demand for service factors described above under I.1.a.,and/or other relevant metrics.b) Recommend staffing levels in relation to demand for service. Forecast future staffing in lightof estimated changes to the demand for service factors described above.c) Review existing administrative and operational business processes to identify pain pointsthat could be streamlined or other potential efficiencies.d) Review the use of overtime to meet staffing needs. If applicable, recommend changes toovertime policies, management, or controls to best use overtime to maximize both costefficiency and scheduling flexibility.e) Review the use of sworn vs. civilian personnel, particularly the use of civilian personnel inadministrative or technical roles. If applicable, recommend changes to how and wherecivilian and sworn personnel are deployed to make the best use of their skills and expertise.
 
Product Code(s): 91885
 
Agency Information
Issuing Agency: City of Minneapolis
State: Minnesota
Agency Type: State and Local
Contact: Renae Youngs
Phone: Not Stated
Email: renae.youngs@minneapolismn.gov

Received Date:  03/23/2020
Close Date:  Not Stated
Delivery Point:  45600 WOODLAND ROAD STERLING VA 20166
Download documents online
Bid Documents
Request Future Documents
Bid Awards
Specifications:
This notice is in accordance with FAR Subpart 5.2, Synopses of Proposed Contract Actions. The U.S. Department of the Interior, Bureau of Safety Environmental Enforcement (BSEE), Acquisition Operations Branch, is the contracting office for this procurement. The purpose of this notice is to announce an award to Acadian Ambulance Service, Inc, on a sole source bases for a Time and Materials Purchase Order for $199,356.75 for the base period of 90 days with the potential of 3, 90 day option periods. Acadian Ambulance Service, Inc. will provide COVID-19 pre-screening services for the locations of New Orleans, LA, Lafayette, LA and Lake Jackson, TX. The Government attempted to find additional contractors, but due to the urgency of this requirement and to allow BSEE Inspectors to perform mission critical functions, it was determined that Acadian Ambulance Service, Inc. was the only company immediately available to provide services in all three of the locations and be able to deploy in such a quick time frame. In accordance with the FAR the Government will review the requirement and attempt to obtain competition during the base period of the requirement. This is not a request for competitive quotes; however, all interested sources that believe they can meet future requirements, shall submit a capability statement to the Contracting Office on this notice. Information received as a result of this notice will be considered solely for future purposes to determine if a competitive acquisition can be achieved. All submissions should be sent no later than April 10 to David Jablonski at David.Jablonski@bsee.gov. Telephone calls regarding this matter will neither be accepted nor returned.
